    "# **SDP-Symresack: Lexicographic Symmetry Breaking for Semidefinite Programs**\n",
    "\n",
    "We introduce **SDP-symresacks**: linear constraints that impose a lexicographic ordering on the entries of a symmetric positive semidefinite matrix to select a canonical representative from each symmetry orbit. These constraints, called **FD-inequalities** (first-different inequalities), provably preserve the optimal value of any SDP whose feasible set and objective are invariant under a single permutation (i.e., a cyclic subgroup generated by one permutation). The proof is elementary: every orbit is finite, so it contains a lexicographically maximal element, which by construction satisfies the FD-inequalities and achieves the same objective value as any other orbit member.\n",
    "\n",
    "We contrast FD-inequalities with the group-averaging approach of Gatermann and Parrilo<sup>[[4]](#ref4)</sup> (GP1). For pure SDPs with linear objectives and convex feasible sets, both methods are theoretically safe: the orbit average is feasible and achieves the same objective value. The key difference appears in **mixed-integer** contexts, where averaging destroys integrality and FD-inequalities do not.\n",
    "\n",
    "The complete graph $K_3$ under the cyclic subgroup $C_3 = \\langle (1\\;2\\;3) \\rangle \\leq S_3$ is used throughout as a concrete illustration of all definitions.\n",
    "\n",
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "s1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 1. Background: SDPs and Symmetry\n",
    "\n",
    "An SDP is an optimization problem where we maximize a linear function $\\langle C, X \\rangle$ over symmetric matrices $X$. The matrices must be positive semidefinite ($X \\succeq 0$) and must satisfy a set of linear constraints $\\langle A_i, X \\rangle = b_i$ for $i = 1,\\ldots,m$.<sup>[[6]](#ref6)</sup>\n",
    "\n",
    "**Symmetry by conjugation.** A permutation $\\pi \\in S_n$ acts on a matrix by swapping rows and columns: $\\pi \\cdot X = P_\\pi X P_\\pi^{\\mathsf{T}}$, using the permutation matrix $P_\\pi$. Since $P_\\pi$ is orthogonal, conjugation preserves the eigenvalues and therefore positive semidefiniteness.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Symmetry group.** A subgroup $G \\leq S_n$ is a **symmetry group** of the SDP if applying any $\\pi \\in G$ to a feasible matrix gives another feasible matrix with the same objective value. The **orbit** of $X$ under $G$ is $\\mathcal{O}(X) = \\{ \\pi \\cdot X : \\pi \\in G \\}$ — the set of all matrices reachable by applying elements of the group. In a symresack, $G$ is generated by a single permutation, so $G = \\langle \\gamma \\rangle \\cong C_k$ where $k$ is the order of $\\gamma$. For a comprehensive treatment of symmetry in integer programming, see Margot.<sup>[[5]](#ref5)</sup>\n",
    "\n",
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "29d86e9c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2. The MaxCut Problem on $K_3$\n",
    "\n",
    "#### **Integer Formulation**\n",
    "\n",
    "The **maximum cut** on $K_3 = (V,E)$ with $V = \\{1,2,3\\}$ and unit weights seeks a partition $V = S \\cup \\bar{S}$ maximizing crossing edges. Assigning $x_i = +1$ if $i \\in S$ and $x_i = -1$ if $i \\in \\bar{S}$, the cut value equals $\\frac{1}{2}\\sum_{(i,j)\\in E}(1 - x_i x_j)$. The **integer optimal value is $2$**, achieved by the three 2-1 partitions.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### **SDP Relaxation**\n",
    "\n",
    "The Goemans-Williamson SDP relaxation replaces $x_i \\in \\{-1,+1\\}$ with unit vectors $\\mathbf{v}_i$ and sets $X_{ij} = \\mathbf{v}_i \\cdot \\mathbf{v}_j$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\max \\frac{3 - X_{12} - X_{13} - X_{23}}{2} \\quad \\text{s.t.} \\quad X = \\begin{bmatrix}1 & a & b \\\\ a & 1 & c \\\\ b & c & 1\\end{bmatrix} \\succeq 0\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "with $(a,b,c) := (X_{12}, X_{13}, X_{23})$. The PSD condition is $\\det X = 1 + 2abc - a^2 - b^2 - c^2 \\geq 0$. By optimality conditions on the boundary $\\det X = 0$, the minimum of $a+b+c$ subject to PSD is $-3/2$, achieved at $a = b = c = -1/2$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\text{SDP optimal value} = \\frac{3-(-3/2)}{2} = \\frac{9}{4} \\;>\\; 2 = \\text{integer optimal}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "#### **Integer-Feasible Solutions**\n",
    "\n",
    "Integer feasibility requires $X_{ij} = x_i x_j$ for some $x \\in \\{-1,+1\\}^3$. Since $x$ and $-x$ give the same matrix, there are $2^3/2 = 4$ distinct integer-feasible matrices:\n",
    "\n",
    "<div align=\"center\">\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{array}{cccc}\n",
    "\\hline\n",
    "(a,\\; b,\\; c) & \\textbf{\\(\\det X\\)} & \\textbf{PSD?} & \\textbf{Cut value} \\\\\n",
    "\\hline\\hline\n",
    "(1,\\;\\;1,\\;\\;1) & 0 & \\checkmark & (3-3)/2 = 0 \\\\\n",
    "(1,\\;-1,\\;-1) & 0 & \\checkmark & (3+1)/2 = 2 \\leftarrow optimal \\\\\n",
    "(-1,\\;\\;1,\\;-1) & 0 & \\checkmark & (3+1)/2 = 2 \\leftarrow optimal \\\\\n",
    "(-1,\\;-1,\\;\\;1) & 0 & \\checkmark & (3+1)/2 = 2 \\leftarrow optimal \\\\\n",
    "\\hline\n",
    "\\end{array}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "</div>\n",
    "\n",
    "**Verification** for $(1,-1,-1)$: $\\det X = 1 + 2(1)(-1)(-1) - 1 - 1 - 1 = 0 \\geq 0$ ✓. Cut value: $(3-1+1+1)/2 = 2$ ✓.\n",
    "\n",
    "All four matrices lie on the PSD boundary ($\\det X = 0$, rank $\\leq 2$). The three with cut value $2$ correspond to the three 2-1 partitions of $K_3$.\n",
    "\n",
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "s2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2. Vectorization and FD-Inequalities\n",
    "\n",
    "#### **Vectorization**\n",
    "\n",
    "Read the upper triangle of $X \\in \\mathbb{S}^n$ row by row. For $n = 3$, the vectorization order is\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\operatorname{vec}(X) = (\\overbrace{X_{11}}^{1}, \\overbrace{X_{12}}^{2}, \\overbrace{X_{13}}^{3},\\; \\overbrace{X_{22}}^{4}, \\overbrace{X_{23}}^{5}, \\overbrace{X_{33}}^{6})\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "In general, for $n \\times n$ matrices:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\operatorname{vec}(X) = (X_{11}, X_{12}, \\ldots, X_{1n},\\; X_{22}, X_{23}, \\ldots, X_{2n},\\; \\ldots,\\; X_{nn}) \\in \\mathbb{R}^{n(n+1)/2}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "#### **Lexicographic Order**\n",
    "\n",
    "The **lexicographic order** $\\geq_{\\operatorname{lex}}$ on $\\mathbb{R}^N$ compares vectors entry by entry: $u \\geq_{\\operatorname{lex}} v$ iff $u = v$, or the first index $k$ with $u_k \\neq v_k$ satisfies $u_k > v_k$.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### **FD-Inequalities**\n",
    "\n",
    "For a non-identity $\\pi \\in G$, let $k(\\pi)$ be the smallest off-diagonal index $(i,j)$ that $\\pi$ actually moves (i.e., $\\pi^{-1}(i) \\neq i$ or $\\pi^{-1}(j) \\neq j$). The **FD-inequality** for $\\pi$ is\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "X_{k(\\pi)} \\geq (\\pi \\cdot X)_{k(\\pi)}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "which compares the two entries at the first position where $X$ and $\\pi \\cdot X$ could differ. The **SDP-Symresack** is the set of feasible matrices whose vectorization is lexicographically maximal in its orbit:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\mathcal{F}_G = \\big\\{ X \\in \\mathcal{F} : \\operatorname{vec}(X) \\geq_{\\operatorname{lex}} \\operatorname{vec}(\\pi \\cdot X), \\;\\; \\forall \\pi \\in G \\big\\}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Since $G$ is finite, this requires finitely many linear constraints. For the action of $G$ on the vectorization by coordinate permutation, imposing one FD-inequality per generator of $G$ suffices for all group elements. This is a known result from the symresack literature (Hojny &amp; Pfetsch, 2019, Lemma 2.3).<sup>[[2]](#ref2)</sup>\n",
    "\n",
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "s3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 3. FD-Inequalities for $C_3 = \\langle (1\\;2\\;3) \\rangle$ on $K_3$\n",
    "\n",
    "For $n = 3$ with unit diagonal, the off-diagonal entries are $(a,b,c) = (X_{12}, X_{13}, X_{23})$.\n",
    "\n",
    "Each permutation $\\pi \\in C_3 = \\langle (1\\;2\\;3) \\rangle$ acts by conjugation:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "X = \\begin{bmatrix}1 & a & b \\\\ a & 1 & c \\\\ b & c & 1\\end{bmatrix}\n",
    "\\; \\xrightarrow{\\pi} \\; P_\\pi X P_\\pi^{\\mathsf{T}}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "#### **Deriving the FD-Inequalities**\n",
    "\n",
    "For the single generator $\\gamma = (1\\;2\\;3)$ of $C_3$:\n",
    "\n",
    "**Generator $\\gamma = (1\\;2\\;3)$** (cyclic rotation $1 \\to 2 \\to 3 \\to 1$):\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "P_{(123)} X P_{(123)}^{\\mathsf{T}} = \\begin{bmatrix}1 & c & a \\\\ c & 1 & b \\\\ a & b & 1\\end{bmatrix}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "First difference at index 2: $a$ vs $c$. **FD-ineq:** $a \\geq c$, i.e., $X_{12} \\geq X_{23}$.\n",
    "\n",
    "**$\\gamma^2 = (1\\;3\\;2)$** (the inverse rotation):\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "P_{(132)} X P_{(132)}^{\\mathsf{T}} = \\begin{bmatrix}1 & b & c \\\\ b & 1 & a \\\\ c & a & 1\\end{bmatrix}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "First difference at index 2: $a$ vs $b$. **FD-ineq:** $a \\geq b$, i.e., $X_{12} \\geq X_{13}$.\n",
    "\n",
    "The two FD-inequalities for $C_3$ are therefore\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\boxed{X_{12} \\geq X_{13},\\; X_{12} \\geq X_{23}} \\qquad (a \\geq b,\\; a \\geq c)\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "#### **Orbit Structure**\n",
    "\n",
    "<div align=\"center\">\n",
    "\n",
    "**Table A.** Orbit of $(a,b,c)$ under $C_3$.\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{array}{ccc}\n",
    "\\hline\n",
    "\\textbf{\\(\\pi\\)} & \\textbf{\\(\\pi\\)} \\cdot (a,b,c) & \\textbf{Permutation} \\\\\n",
    "\\hline\\hline\n",
    "e & (a,b,c) & \\text{identity} \\\\\n",
    "(123) & (c,a,b) & 3\\text{-cycle } 1\\to2\\to3 \\\\\n",
    "(132) & (b,c,a) & 3\\text{-cycle } 1\\to3\\to2 \\\\\n",
    "\\hline\n",
    "\\end{array}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "</div>\n",
    "\n",
    "The three elements of $C_3$ produce the cyclic permutations of $(a,b,c)$. The FD-inequalities $a \\geq b$ and $a \\geq c$ pick exactly one representative from this orbit.\n",
    "\n",
    "These two FD-inequalities imply $\\operatorname{vec}(X) \\geq_{\\operatorname{lex}} \\operatorname{vec}(\\pi \\cdot X)$ for all three $\\pi \\in C_3$.\n",
    "\n",
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "s4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 4. FD-Inequalities Preserve the SDP Optimum\n",
    "\n",
    "**Theorem (Preservation of SDP Optimum).** If $G$ is a symmetry group of the SDP, then\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\max_{X \\in \\mathcal{F}} \\langle C, X \\rangle = \\max_{X \\in \\mathcal{F}_G} \\langle C, X \\rangle\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "so adding FD-inequalities does not weaken the bound.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Proof.** Adding more constraints can only shrink the feasible set, so $\\max_{\\mathcal{F}_G} \\leq \\max_{\\mathcal{F}}$ is automatic. The interesting part is showing that the optimum stays the same.\n",
    "\n",
    "Take any optimal solution $X^* \\in \\mathcal{F}$. Since $G$ is finite, the orbit $\\mathcal{O}(X^*) = \\{ \\pi \\cdot X^* : \\pi \\in G \\}$ is a finite set. Among its elements, pick the one that is lexicographically largest, call it $\\hat{X}$.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Feasibility:** $\\hat{X}$ belongs to the orbit, and the orbit is inside $\\mathcal{F}$ because $G$ preserves feasibility.\n",
    "- **Objective value:** $\\langle C, \\hat{X} \\rangle = \\langle C, X^* \\rangle$ because $G$ preserves the objective.\n",
    "- **FD-inequalities:** For any $\\pi \\in G$, the matrix $\\pi \\cdot \\hat{X}$ is also in the orbit. By definition, $\\hat{X}$ is the lexicographically largest in the orbit, so $\\operatorname{vec}(\\hat{X}) \\geq_{\\operatorname{lex}} \\operatorname{vec}(\\pi \\cdot \\hat{X})$, which is exactly the condition for belonging to $\\mathcal{F}_G$.\n",
    "\n",
    "Therefore $\\max_{\\mathcal{F}_G} \\geq \\langle C, \\hat{X} \\rangle = \\max_{\\mathcal{F}}$, completing the proof. $\\square$\n",
    "\n",
    "**Remark (Integrality).** The proof does not rely on convexity, so it works even when $\\mathcal{F}$ includes integer constraints. If $X^*$ is integer-feasible and $G$ preserves integrality (true for permutation groups), then $\\hat{X}$ is also integer-feasible and optimal. This is the key advantage over GP1 averaging.\n",
    "\n",
    "The lexicographically largest element in an orbit is unique, so $\\mathcal{F}_G$ contains exactly one matrix from each orbit.\n",
    "\n",
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "s5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 5. Comparison with GP1 Averaging\n",
    "\n",
    "Gatermann and Parrilo<sup>[[4]](#ref4)</sup> propose restricting the SDP to the **fixed-point subspace** under $G$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\mathcal{F}_{\\operatorname{GP1}} = \\big\\{ X \\in \\mathcal{F} : \\pi \\cdot X = X, \\;\\; \\forall \\pi \\in G \\big\\}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "This collapses all entries sharing a $G$-orbit of positions to a single variable, reducing the problem dimension.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why GP1 works for pure SDPs.** Take any optimal $X^* \\in \\mathcal{F}$. The group average\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\bar{X} = \\frac{1}{|G|} \\sum_{\\pi \\in G} \\pi \\cdot X^*\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "lies in $\\mathcal{F}_{\\operatorname{GP1}}$ (by construction) and satisfies $\\langle C, \\bar{X} \\rangle = \\langle C, X^* \\rangle$ (by linearity and $G$-invariance of $C$). So $\\max_{\\mathcal{F}_{\\operatorname{GP1}}} = \\max_{\\mathcal{F}}$ for pure SDPs.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why GP1 fails with integers.** The averaging map $X^* \\mapsto \\bar{X}$ does **not** preserve integrality. If $X^*$ has $\\{-1,+1\\}$ off-diagonal entries, $\\bar{X}$ is generically non-integer. When the $G$-invariant subspace contains no integer-optimal solutions, GP1 loses the true optimum entirely.\n",
    "\n",
    "<div align=\"center\">\n",
    "\n",
    "**Table 1.** Comparison of FD-inequalities and GP1 averaging.\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{array}{lcc}\n",
    "\\hline\n",
    "\\textbf{Property} & \\textbf{FD-inequalities} & \\textbf{GP1 averaging} \\\\\n",
    "\\hline\\hline\n",
    "\\text{Preserves pure SDP optimum} & \\checkmark & \\checkmark \\\\\n",
    "\\text{Reduces problem dimension} & \\times & \\checkmark \\\\\n",
    "\\text{Preserves integer optimum} & \\checkmark & \\text{Not guaranteed} \\\\\n",
    "\\text{Linear constraints} & \\checkmark & \\checkmark \\\\\n",
    "\\text{Unique orbit representative} & \\checkmark & \\text{Only } G\\text{-invariant orbit} \\\\\n",
    "\\hline\n",
    "\\end{array}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "</div>\n",
    "\n",
    "GP1 is better for solving pure SDPs efficiently. FD-inequalities are the right choice when integer feasibility must be preserved, for instance in branch-and-bound for mixed-integer SDPs.\n",
    "\n",
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "s6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 6. Illustration on $K_3$\n",
    "\n",
    "<div align=\"center\">\n",
    "\n",
    "**The complete graph $K_3$.** All edges have unit weight.\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{pmatrix}\n",
    "0 & 1 & 1 \\\\\n",
    "1 & 0 & 1 \\\\\n",
    "1 & 1 & 0\n",
    "\\end{pmatrix}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "</div>\n",
    "\n",
    "We apply the ideas above to the MaxCut SDP on $K_3$ with $C_3$ symmetry (cyclic rotations). The Goemans--Williamson relaxation<sup>[[1]](#ref1)</sup> with unit weights is\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\max \\; \\frac{3 - a - b - c}{2} \\quad \\text{s.t.} \\quad\n",
    "X = \\begin{bmatrix} 1 & a & b \\\\ a & 1 & c \\\\ b & c & 1 \\end{bmatrix} \\succeq 0\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $\\{a,b,c\\} = \\{X_{12}, X_{13}, X_{23}\\}$. The PSD condition is $\\det X = 1 + 2abc - a^2 - b^2 - c^2 \\geq 0$ with $|a|,|b|,|c| \\leq 1$.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### **$C_3$ Symmetry**\n",
    "\n",
    "$C_3$ cyclically rotates $\\{a,b,c\\}$ by conjugation, and the objective depends only on $a+b+c$, so $G = C_3$ is a symmetry group.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### **SDP Optimal Value**\n",
    "\n",
    "Minimising $a+b+c$ over the PSD region gives $a = b = c = -1/2$, yielding\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\text{SDP optimal} = \\frac{3 - (-3/2)}{2} = \\frac{9}{4}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The true integer max-cut of $K_3$ is $2$, so the integrality gap is $9/8$. This is consistent with the Goemans--Williamson relaxation: the SDP value $9/4$ upper-bounds the true max-cut, yielding an approximation ratio of $8/9 \\approx 0.889$, which is tighter than the worst-case GW bound $\\alpha_{\\text{GW}} \\approx 0.878$.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### **FD-Inequalities**\n",
    "\n",
    "The two FD-inequalities are $a \\geq b$ and $a \\geq c$. The SDP optimum $a = b = c = -1/2$ satisfies them with equality, so it stays feasible and the optimal value $9/4$ is preserved.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### **GP1 Averaging**\n",
    "\n",
    "GP1 forces $a = b = c = t$. The PSD condition gives $t \\geq -1/2$, and the optimum is again $9/4$ at $t = -1/2$.\n",
    "\n",
    "On this example all three approaches give the same SDP bound of $9/4$. The difference appears only at the integer level: GP1 turns $\\{-1,+1\\}$ solutions into fractions, while FD-inequalities keep exactly one integer-optimal orbit representative. See the companion notebook (Version C) for that analysis.\n",
    "\n",
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "s7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 7. Extensions\n",
    "\n",
    "The extensions below are derived by analogy with binary symresacks.<sup>[[3]](#ref3)</sup> They are presented as directions for future work and have not been formally verified for the SDP-symresack setting.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Symmetric group $S_n$.** FD-inequalities from the adjacent transpositions $\\{(i\\;i{+}1)\\}$ enforce\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "X_{12} \\geq X_{13} \\geq \\cdots \\geq X_{1n}, \\quad\n",
    "X_{23} \\geq X_{24} \\geq \\cdots \\geq X_{2n}, \\quad \\ldots\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "a total of $\\binom{n}{2} - 1$ linear constraints. The canonical orbit representative is the unique matrix with sorted off-diagonal entries.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Cyclic groups $\\mathbb{Z}_k$.** For a generator $\\sigma$ of order $k$, we have $k-1$ constraints:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\operatorname{vec}(X) \\geq_{\\operatorname{lex}} \\operatorname{vec}(\\sigma \\cdot X) \\geq_{\\operatorname{lex}} \\cdots \\geq_{\\operatorname{lex}} \\operatorname{vec}(\\sigma^{k-1} \\cdot X)\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "**Signed permutations $B_n$.** For the hyperoctahedral group (permutations with sign flips), FD-inequalities use absolute values in the first stage (largest magnitude entry per orbit) and sign ordering afterwards.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Signed permutations \$B_n\$.** For the hyperoctahedral group (permutations with sign flips), FD-inequalities use absolute values in the first stage and sign ordering afterwards.\n",\n    "\n",\n    "**Orbit-wise application.** When the group action splits off-diagonal positions into multiple orbits, FD-inequalities apply independently within each orbit. The total constraint count is $\\sum_{\\text{orbits}} (|\\text{orbit}| - 1)$, always less than the number of off-diagonal positions.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### **Further Directions**\n",
    "\n",
    "The extensions above are derived by analogy with binary symresacks and are presented as directions for future work. Open questions include:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Do the $\\binom{n}{2}-1$ FD-inequalities for $S_n$ exactly describe the lex-max region?\n",
    "- Can the PSD cone structure be exploited to derive stronger inequalities than the FD-inequalities?\n",
    "- How do FD-inequalities interact with other SDP symmetry reduction techniques?\n",
    "\n",
    "---"
   ]
  },
